{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RVGigpmgvUGPH11fVCrMUG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is DNS resolution for `es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. The headless service was just created, and ES might be trying to resolve it before DNS has propagated. But wait, only `es-0` is running - which means `es-1` and `es-2` haven't started yet. The StatefulSet creates pods sequentially, and `es-0` might be waiting on the readiness probe before `es-1` starts.\n\nThe problem is:\n1. `es-0` is running but not ready (readiness probe failing)\n2. The StatefulSet won't create `es-1` until `es-0` becomes Ready\n3. But `es-0` can't become Ready until the cluster forms, which requires other nodes\n4. The DNS resolution failure for the headless service is likely temporary - the service exists but has no pods backing it yet since only `es-0` is running\n\nActually, I see the real issue now. For a headless service without a ClusterIP, DNS only resolves if there are ready endpoints behind it. Since no ES pods are ready yet, the DNS won't resolve - this creates a circular dependency where pods need DNS to discover each other, but DNS needs ready pods to work.\n\nThe fix is to configure `discovery.seed_hosts` with the individual pod hostnames directly instead of relying on the headless service name - using addresses like `es-0.es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, `es-1.es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, and `es-2.es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. The StatefulSet's headless service automatically provides DNS entries for each pod hostname even before they're ready.\n\nI also need to change the StatefulSet to use `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` so all three pods start at once instead of sequentially, and simplify the readiness probe to just check if Elasticsearch is running rather than requiring cluster health to be yellow. records are created immediately when the pod gets an IP, so the individual pod hostnames should resolve fine. I need to simplify the readiness probe though—checking cluster health with `wait_for_status=yellow` will block indefinitely if the cluster can't form. Instead, I'll use a TCP socket check on port 9200 or a basic curl request to verify Elasticsearch is responding.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":886,"cache_read_input_tokens":34889,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":886},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"88aa9a3a-e056-408c-84ff-72f2233e54a4","uuid":"cec278ed-40ef-43d8-ba43-451c4b5e1395","request_id":"req_011Cc6mujadfZZtgKokxzswZ"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RVGigpmgvUGPH11fVCrMUG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The StatefulSet is starting pods sequentially and `es-0` can't become ready until the cluster forms, which requires all 3 pods. I need to fix two things: use `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` and use individual pod DNS names for discovery."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":886,"cache_read_input_tokens":34889,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":886},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"88aa9a3a-e056-408c-84ff-72f2233e54a4","uuid":"ea074bc5-194b-4e50-af5e-aa5d361b6e70","request_id":"req_011Cc6mujadfZZtgKokxzswZ"}
